Pete Hammond,
"Deadline Hollywood."

00:00:50.510 --> 00:00:55.250
Congratulations on writing
an incredible story.

00:00:55.250 --> 00:01:00.440
Hallie, this is your writing
debut, yes, directing debut,

00:01:00.440 --> 00:01:02.800
and film debut in general?

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:05.882
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
Yeah, it's my debut.

00:01:05.882 --> 00:01:07.160
Yeah.

00:01:07.160 --> 00:01:11.130
SPEAKER 1: So I guess, where
did the idea come from?

00:01:11.130 --> 00:01:12.382
Where did this originate?

00:01:12.382 --> 00:01:14.090
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
It came from a bunch

00:01:14.090 --> 00:01:15.170
of different places.

00:01:15.170 --> 00:01:18.100
I had had the character of Alice
in my head for a long time,

00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:21.050
of this woman who had sort
of made a lot of decisions

00:01:21.050 --> 00:01:23.780
early in life, and then
started questioning them,

00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:25.910
and that kind of
post-separation, post-divorce

00:01:25.910 --> 00:01:27.120
time in a woman's life.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:32.361
And I had a friend who had three
guys move into her family's

00:01:32.361 --> 00:01:33.860
house growing up,
and I just thought

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:36.140
that was such an interesting
idea, and a great setting

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:36.870
for a comedy.

00:01:36.870 --> 00:01:40.430
So I sort of put this
character in that scenario,

00:01:40.430 --> 00:01:43.110
and it all came from there.

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:46.740
SPEAKER 1: So in real life,
was there the sexual tension

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:47.740
that ended up happening?

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:49.864
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: I
actually don't know anything

00:01:49.864 --> 00:01:51.350
about what actually happened.

00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:53.430
It is a fictional film.

00:01:53.430 --> 00:01:55.670
SPEAKER 1: Sure it is, right.

00:01:55.670 --> 00:01:57.710
And Reese and Jon,
how did the two of you

00:01:57.710 --> 00:01:59.660
get onboard the film yourselves?

00:01:59.660 --> 00:02:02.570
REESE WITHERSPOON: I read the
script, and I just loved it.

00:02:02.570 --> 00:02:05.960
I thought it was such an
original idea, and the idea

00:02:05.960 --> 00:02:09.615
that a decision you make
at 25 isn't necessarily

00:02:09.615 --> 00:02:11.490
the right decision for
the rest of your life.

00:02:11.490 --> 00:02:14.073
And I think a lot of people are
at crossroads at certain times

00:02:14.073 --> 00:02:17.340
and trying to figure out
chapter 2 of their life.

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:20.150
And so I met with Hallie,
and she was wildly impressive

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:22.320
and had a great vision for it.

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:24.070
And we went ahead.

00:02:24.070 --> 00:02:25.820
SPEAKER 1: And Jon,
what about you?

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:26.986
JON RUDNITSKY: I mean, same.

00:02:26.986 --> 00:02:29.990
I read the script
and was blown away.

00:02:29.990 --> 00:02:34.250
It's also about three young
filmmakers who move out

00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:35.600
to LA hoping to make it.

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:40.460
And me, Nat, and Pico can all
relate, obviously, to that.

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:43.729
So you know, I was honored
to be a part of it,

00:02:43.729 --> 00:02:45.020
getting to work with these two.

00:02:45.020 --> 00:02:47.561
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: Jon came
in on our first day of casting,

00:02:47.561 --> 00:02:48.620
which is very special.

00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:48.980
SPEAKER 1: Really?

00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:49.710
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: Yeah.

00:02:49.710 --> 00:02:52.160
SPEAKER 1: And so none of you
knew each other beforehand?

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:53.326
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: No, no.

00:02:53.326 --> 00:02:55.100
Not really.

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:57.559
JON RUDNITSKY: I'd heard of you.

00:02:57.559 --> 00:02:59.350
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
We knew who Reese was.

00:02:59.350 --> 00:03:00.966
JON RUDNITSKY: I'd
heard of you, yeah.

00:03:00.966 --> 00:03:03.570
I had seen you in something.

00:03:03.570 --> 00:03:05.320
REESE WITHERSPOON:
What'd you think of me?

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:11.270
SPEAKER 1: Right, so Reese,
you've been acting since,

00:03:11.270 --> 00:03:12.480
what, you were 14, 15?

00:03:12.480 --> 00:03:13.670
REESE WITHERSPOON: Yeah, 14.

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:16.820
SPEAKER 1: And so with hits--
gosh, "Pleasantville" still

00:03:16.820 --> 00:03:19.280
one of my all-time favorites
from when I was younger,

00:03:19.280 --> 00:03:22.360
"Cruel Intentions," "American
Psycho," "Legally Blonde,"

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:23.235
"Sweet Home Alabama."

00:03:23.235 --> 00:03:24.340
[CHEERING]

00:03:25.600 --> 00:03:29.305
This is the "Legally
Blonde" section over here.

00:03:29.305 --> 00:03:31.680
"Sweet Home Alabama," "Walk
the Line," with which you won

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:32.430
the Academy Award.

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:33.480
Again, congratulations.

00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:35.640
REESE WITHERSPOON: Thank you.

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:39.210
SPEAKER 1: So I guess you've
been putting out a movie

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:42.450
a year since you
were a teenager.

00:03:42.450 --> 00:03:45.456
REESE WITHERSPOON: I guess so.

00:03:45.456 --> 00:03:46.830
SPEAKER 1: You
were a child star,

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:48.300
and then went to
be an adult star.

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:50.520
How did you navigate
that complexity

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:55.790
without sort of going a little
bit typically child-star crazy?

00:03:55.790 --> 00:03:58.035
REESE WITHERSPOON: I
mean, I don't know.

00:03:58.035 --> 00:04:00.154
I wasn't really
a big child star.

00:04:00.154 --> 00:04:01.570
I worked in movies,
and my parents

00:04:01.570 --> 00:04:03.403
were very adamant that
I stay in high school

00:04:03.403 --> 00:04:04.600
and that I went to college.

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:07.620
So I didn't really start working
with any kind of regularity

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:09.470
until I was about 19.

00:04:09.470 --> 00:04:13.620
I got a big audition
when I was at Stanford,

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:16.230
and then I had to drop
out to do the movie.

00:04:16.230 --> 00:04:18.480
And then I got another movie,
and I got another movie.

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:19.938
And so it just
started working out.

00:04:19.938 --> 00:04:22.050
But I thought I was
going to be a doctor.

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:24.870
I'm not the kind of person
who would move to LA

00:04:24.870 --> 00:04:26.350
and live in a car.

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:27.320
SPEAKER 1: Your parents
are doctors, right?

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:28.500
REESE WITHERSPOON: Yeah, my
parents are both doctors.

00:04:28.500 --> 00:04:29.310
Yep.

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:31.290
SPEAKER 1: So did they
want you to be doctors?

00:04:31.290 --> 00:04:32.829
Because my parents
were always like,

00:04:32.829 --> 00:04:34.620
you can act with a
computer science degree.

00:04:34.620 --> 00:04:36.787
You can't do computer science
with an acting degree.

00:04:36.787 --> 00:04:38.953
Which was the only advice
I really ever listened to,

00:04:38.953 --> 00:04:39.960
which landed me here.

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:42.501
So thank you, Mom and Dad.

00:04:42.501 --> 00:04:44.610
REESE WITHERSPOON:
That's pretty good.

00:04:44.610 --> 00:04:46.930
Yeah, they wanted
me to be a doctor.

00:04:46.930 --> 00:04:47.780
SPEAKER 1: Really?

00:04:47.780 --> 00:04:48.780
REESE WITHERSPOON: Yeah.

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:51.919
I'm pretty sure they still
want me to be a doctor.

00:04:51.919 --> 00:04:54.210
SPEAKER 1: Do they call you
after they see your movies,

00:04:54.210 --> 00:04:56.430
and like, Reese, we
really wish that you

00:04:56.430 --> 00:04:58.112
had become a brain surgeon.

00:04:58.112 --> 00:04:59.820
REESE WITHERSPOON:
Less after the movies,

00:04:59.820 --> 00:05:02.080
more after I do a talk show
and I talk about them a lot.

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:03.663
They're like, really
wish you wouldn't

00:05:03.663 --> 00:05:05.520
talk about us all that much.

00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:07.989
But they're good sports.

00:05:07.989 --> 00:05:09.780
SPEAKER 1: You grew up
in the South, right?

00:05:09.780 --> 00:05:11.780
REESE WITHERSPOON: I grew up
in Nashville, Tennessee, yeah.

00:05:11.780 --> 00:05:14.404
And my dad was in the military,
so we were all over the place.

00:05:14.404 --> 00:05:16.320
SPEAKER 1: How'd you
kick the Southern accent?

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:19.737
REESE WITHERSPOON: Oh, well, I
got advice when I was about 18.

00:05:19.737 --> 00:05:21.570
I went into a casting
office, and they said,

00:05:21.570 --> 00:05:24.150
you're never going to get work
with that terrible accent.

00:05:24.150 --> 00:05:28.770
So I watched a lot of
TV shows, like "90210."

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:31.500
And I went to watch the way
that they would articulate,

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:35.562
and I would copy
them, like that.

00:05:35.562 --> 00:05:38.039
So really it's Shannon Dougherty
I owe my entire career to.

00:05:38.039 --> 00:05:39.580
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
You got it down.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:40.580
SPEAKER 1: Never would
have guessed that.

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:42.538
REESE WITHERSPOON: Tori
Spelling, Jennie Garth.

00:05:42.538 --> 00:05:44.010
I'm just going to
leave it there.

00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:45.615
SPEAKER 1: That's crazy.

00:05:45.615 --> 00:05:47.490
JON RUDNITSKY: And Luke
Perry, and on and on.

00:05:47.490 --> 00:05:48.180
SPEAKER 1: What's that?

00:05:48.180 --> 00:05:49.545
JON RUDNITSKY: We're just
going through the entire cast

00:05:49.545 --> 00:05:50.570
of "90210."

00:05:50.570 --> 00:05:52.865
REESE WITHERSPOON:
The original cast.

00:05:52.865 --> 00:05:53.950
SPEAKER 1: And Jon.

00:05:53.950 --> 00:05:56.370
So dude, SNL.

00:05:56.370 --> 00:05:59.340
People dream about
being on that show.

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:03.930
How did you make the crossover
from, I guess, sketch comedy TV

00:06:03.930 --> 00:06:05.670
into this movie business?

00:06:05.670 --> 00:06:08.420
JON RUDNITSKY: Well, I wouldn't
have gotten the opportunity

00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:11.280
to even audition for this
had it not been for SNL.

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:15.000
That kind of helped put me in
a room with Hallie and Nancy

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.240
to begin with, which
was pretty crazy to even

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:22.620
have an opportunity to be
considered for this movie.

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:26.287
But my background is in acting.

00:06:26.287 --> 00:06:27.870
I've been doing
theater my whole life,

00:06:27.870 --> 00:06:30.570
and I studied theater at USC.

00:06:30.570 --> 00:06:35.370
So I really have
always wanted to act.

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:38.060
I just happen to do comedy in
addition to that, you know?

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:39.768
SPEAKER 1: (MOCKING)
Happen to do comedy.

00:06:39.768 --> 00:06:42.170
JON RUDNITSKY: I happen
to do comedy, you know?

00:06:42.170 --> 00:06:44.128
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: He's
not from the Midwest,

00:06:44.128 --> 00:06:46.298
so we're not sure where
the accent comes from.

00:06:46.298 --> 00:06:48.548
SPEAKER 1: It's like this
weird Michael Keaton accent.

00:06:48.548 --> 00:06:48.976
JON RUDNITSKY: Is it?

00:06:48.976 --> 00:06:49.476
Is it?

00:06:49.476 --> 00:06:51.220
SPEAKER 1: Or Jack
Nicholson, yeah.

00:06:51.220 --> 00:06:52.905
I happen to do comedy.

00:06:52.905 --> 00:06:55.030
JON RUDNITSKY: I don't know
where it's coming from,

00:06:55.030 --> 00:06:55.530
I don't know.

00:06:55.530 --> 00:06:57.570
Do I do it all the time,
or is it just sometimes?

00:06:57.570 --> 00:06:59.903
REESE WITHERSPOON: No, he
does lots of different voices.

00:06:59.903 --> 00:07:01.860
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
Yeah, he's a comedian.

00:07:01.860 --> 00:07:03.818
JON RUDNITSKY: Yeah,
there's just certain words

00:07:03.818 --> 00:07:04.550
that I just like.

00:07:04.550 --> 00:07:06.240
Like, I like to
say about "a-boat"

00:07:06.240 --> 00:07:08.260
even though I'm from Jersey.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:11.124
But it's more fun
to say "a-boat"

00:07:11.124 --> 00:07:12.290
and I'm going to the "bahr."

00:07:12.290 --> 00:07:13.890
Like, I'm going to the "bahr."

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:17.442
Why wouldn't you choose
to say it that way?

00:07:17.442 --> 00:07:19.650
You could, just take what
you like from every accent,

00:07:19.650 --> 00:07:21.067
I guess.

00:07:21.067 --> 00:07:23.150
SPEAKER 1: Like "I pahked
the cah at Havahd Yahd."

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:24.699
JON RUDNITSKY: There you go.

00:07:24.699 --> 00:07:25.740
SPEAKER 1: So Hallie now.

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:28.100
You turned 30 pretty
recently, yes?

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:29.840
I don't want to out
you here, your age.

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:30.260
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
No, that's fine.

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:31.297
I'm good with it.

00:07:31.297 --> 00:07:32.880
SPEAKER 1: I bring
this up because you

00:07:32.880 --> 00:07:35.100
make me feel really
insignificant with my own life

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:37.080
decisions.

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:39.570
Being older than that
and having seen now

00:07:39.570 --> 00:07:42.499
what you have
accomplished, I guess

00:07:42.499 --> 00:07:44.790
it makes me feel like I've
had a few wrong choices when

00:07:44.790 --> 00:07:47.100
I was 25.

00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:49.170
But you started your
own acting career

00:07:49.170 --> 00:07:51.217
when you were like, four, yeah?

00:07:51.217 --> 00:07:52.800
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
Well, it's funny.

00:07:52.800 --> 00:07:54.770
I'm being asked that
a lot, but I wasn't it

00:07:54.770 --> 00:07:57.060
in no way a child actor.

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:00.400
My parents forced me to be
in their films basically.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:02.070
But I'm very grateful,
because now it's

00:08:02.070 --> 00:08:04.614
kind of like I have
this personal connection

00:08:04.614 --> 00:08:06.030
and a little bit
of a photo album.

00:08:06.030 --> 00:08:08.220
But no, I was always
on their sets,

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:09.904
so they'd throw me in the movie.

00:08:09.904 --> 00:08:11.820
But it wasn't because I
wanted to be an actor.

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:13.524
SPEAKER 1: And who
are your parents?

00:08:13.524 --> 00:08:14.940
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
Nancy Meyers,

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:17.490
the producer of our
movie, and my dad

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:20.940
is Charles Shyer, who was her
partner for a lot of my life.

00:08:20.940 --> 00:08:22.020
SPEAKER 1: A long time.

00:08:22.020 --> 00:08:25.050
And for those who don't
know, the two of them

00:08:25.050 --> 00:08:28.327
have produced many things, such
as "The Intern," "The Holiday,"

00:08:28.327 --> 00:08:30.660
"It's Complicated," "Parent
Trap," "Baby Boom," "Private

00:08:30.660 --> 00:08:32.940
Benjamin," "Father
of the Bride."

00:08:32.940 --> 00:08:36.299
If you've heard of any of those,
came from this family lineage.

00:08:36.299 --> 00:08:39.120
And now the apple has not
fallen far from the tree.

00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:41.027
This movie is
absolutely incredible,

00:08:41.027 --> 00:08:42.360
and you're standing on your own.

00:08:42.360 --> 00:08:44.310
So thank you for
continuing this.

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:48.310
And it is such a fun movie.

00:08:48.310 --> 00:08:51.190
Was it as fun to write as--

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:53.310
I guess the question is,
was it as fun to write

00:08:53.310 --> 00:08:54.750
as it was for us to watch?

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:57.010
JON RUDNITSKY: Oh, boy.

00:08:57.010 --> 00:08:58.380
Got a little over-excited.

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:01.149
SPEAKER 1: That is
a literal mic drop.

00:09:01.149 --> 00:09:02.440
JON RUDNITSKY: Come on, Google.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:05.980
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: It was
very fun to make the movie.

00:09:05.980 --> 00:09:07.650
I love writing.

00:09:07.650 --> 00:09:10.490
It's where I identify most
in the filmmaking process,

00:09:10.490 --> 00:09:12.855
is with writing.

00:09:12.855 --> 00:09:14.980
I mean, in my case, I don't
have a writing partner.

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:17.230
So you're completely alone
with these characters,

00:09:17.230 --> 00:09:19.420
and there's so much
fun to be had there.

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:22.420
But it's really
challenging writing a movie

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:25.180
and layering your characters.

00:09:25.180 --> 00:09:26.610
And

00:09:26.610 --> 00:09:31.180
I think I did probably upwards
of 30 drafts of this script.

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:36.450
I did 15 on my own, then
I gave it to my mom.

00:09:36.450 --> 00:09:39.487
Then another 15
came out of that.

00:09:39.487 --> 00:09:41.820
REESE WITHERSPOON: Is that
scary, giving it to your mom?

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:42.275
I'd be like,

00:09:42.275 --> 00:09:42.774
[SHUDDERS]

00:09:42.774 --> 00:09:45.190
SPEAKER 1: Just hands it
back with a big, red X on it.

00:09:45.190 --> 00:09:46.773
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
No, because she's

00:09:46.773 --> 00:09:48.340
the only person I give it to.

00:09:48.340 --> 00:09:51.359
I gave it to her, and she has
such thoughtful, good notes.

00:09:51.359 --> 00:09:53.650
I think good notes is just
raising the right questions.

00:09:53.650 --> 00:09:55.941
She never said, you should
do this, you should do that.

00:09:55.941 --> 00:09:58.546
It would just say,
why did they break up?

00:09:58.546 --> 00:09:59.920
Just raising those
questions that

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:03.550
make you go home and think for
so long, like, oh my god, why?

00:10:03.550 --> 00:10:06.557
I don't know, and I
have to figure this out.

00:10:06.557 --> 00:10:08.140
So I don't even
remember the question,

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:10.884
but yeah, writing is a lot
of work and super rewarding.

00:10:10.884 --> 00:10:11.800
SPEAKER 1: Was it fun?

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:13.133
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: It was fun.

00:10:13.133 --> 00:10:14.530
I love to write.

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:16.360
There's this great
Joan Didion quote,

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:18.800
"I don't know what I'm thinking
until I write it down."

00:10:18.800 --> 00:10:20.260
And I really identify with that.

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:22.676
Sometimes you just don't know
how you feel about something

00:10:22.676 --> 00:10:24.370
until you just write it down.

00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:26.440
SPEAKER 1: That's interesting.

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:29.530
As someone who writes because
I have to answer emails,

00:10:29.530 --> 00:10:31.858
I appreciate someone who
does it for recreation.

00:10:36.864 --> 00:10:38.530
You grew up in the
industry, you grew up

00:10:38.530 --> 00:10:42.220
around very successful parents,
and being on sets all the time.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:46.150
Obviously you have written
a maturity into this film

00:10:46.150 --> 00:10:48.610
that I wouldn't have
expected from someone

00:10:48.610 --> 00:10:52.890
I guess as young as you are,
from a certain perspective.

00:10:52.890 --> 00:10:54.620
So where did that
maturity come from?

00:10:54.620 --> 00:10:58.172
Where did your larger view on
relationships and life happen?

00:10:58.172 --> 00:11:00.130
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: You
know, I think for me I

00:11:00.130 --> 00:11:02.530
was trying a little bit to
honor the medium of film,

00:11:02.530 --> 00:11:05.820
which I respect so much.

00:11:05.820 --> 00:11:08.290
Film is forever,
and I didn't want

00:11:08.290 --> 00:11:09.970
to write about trivial issues.

00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:13.330
So for me, the themes of
family and divorce and starting

00:11:13.330 --> 00:11:14.930
over are important.

00:11:14.930 --> 00:11:21.280
So that's kind of why I think
Alice's story and crossroads is

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:24.700
a little bit weightier and
realer then the issues of sort

00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:27.520
of which guy.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:32.420
The kind of like,
20-something story.

00:11:32.420 --> 00:11:34.420
SPEAKER 1: And I
enjoy in this that it

00:11:34.420 --> 00:11:38.420
doesn't take the normal
slapstick kind of silly turns

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:39.820
that romcoms--

00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:42.210
romantic comedies--
do in most cases.

00:11:42.210 --> 00:11:43.480
So it was a pleasant surprise.

00:11:43.480 --> 00:11:44.650
And I think that's
why, of course,

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:45.700
today the reviews
are coming out,

00:11:45.700 --> 00:11:46.949
and they're all very positive.

00:11:46.949 --> 00:11:50.560
So you've done a good job there.

00:11:50.560 --> 00:11:52.210
Regarding the
characters, I guess.

00:11:52.210 --> 00:11:54.970
So we saw in the preview
there's lots of other people

00:11:54.970 --> 00:11:55.780
in it, obviously.

00:11:55.780 --> 00:11:57.655
It's not just the three
of these people here.

00:11:57.655 --> 00:12:00.160
Or the two of them
and a director.

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:03.100
Michael Sheen is
Alice's husband.

00:12:03.100 --> 00:12:05.720
Candice Bergen is Alice's mom.

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:08.110
We've got Lake Bell, who's
a wonderful addition.

00:12:08.110 --> 00:12:10.060
How did all of these
wonderful people

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:14.710
come to get attached to this
first-time director's film?

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:16.134
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
Well, casting

00:12:16.134 --> 00:12:17.800
is such an important
part of the process

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:20.680
because you're sort of handing
your character off to somebody

00:12:20.680 --> 00:12:22.138
and letting them
make it their own.

00:12:22.138 --> 00:12:26.650
So it's such an important thing,
and we thought really deeply

00:12:26.650 --> 00:12:27.250
about this.

00:12:27.250 --> 00:12:29.680
And it was a really
nice mix, I think,

00:12:29.680 --> 00:12:31.760
of newcomers and
seasoned actors.

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:33.670
And I think that mix
added something fresh

00:12:33.670 --> 00:12:34.450
to the equation.

00:12:34.450 --> 00:12:36.820
It really felt like there
was different generations

00:12:36.820 --> 00:12:37.460
in this movie.

00:12:37.460 --> 00:12:40.910
And I have to say, we
sent it to these people.

00:12:40.910 --> 00:12:43.270
And sometimes you think
you'll never hear back.

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:44.830
And a lot of them responded.

00:12:44.830 --> 00:12:48.570
And my mom had worked with
Bell before, so we knew her.

00:12:48.570 --> 00:12:52.360
But the rest of the actors in
this movie were just good old

00:12:52.360 --> 00:12:55.390
fashioned sending in the script
and hoping they'll say yes.

00:12:55.390 --> 00:12:56.020
REESE WITHERSPOON:
You have to realize

00:12:56.020 --> 00:12:57.770
as an actor you don't
get a lot of scripts

00:12:57.770 --> 00:12:59.590
where you get to play
a character anymore.

00:12:59.590 --> 00:13:00.100
SPEAKER 1: Really?

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:01.849
REESE WITHERSPOON:
Yeah, it's pretty rare.

00:13:01.849 --> 00:13:05.647
And to have a fully fleshed-out
character with a beginning,

00:13:05.647 --> 00:13:07.480
and a middle, and an
end, or a real journey,

00:13:07.480 --> 00:13:10.570
or real lines to say,
or humor is really

00:13:10.570 --> 00:13:11.939
an anomaly these days.

00:13:11.939 --> 00:13:13.480
I mean, you're
honestly just reacting

00:13:13.480 --> 00:13:14.510
to a green screen going,

00:13:14.510 --> 00:13:16.002
[GASP]

00:13:16.002 --> 00:13:18.460
And then to the director you're
like, what am I staring at?

00:13:18.460 --> 00:13:20.959
And he's like, I'm not sure,
we're going to put it in later.

00:13:20.959 --> 00:13:25.060
But just give me six
different reactions to it.

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:27.610
So most actors are
starving to do something

00:13:27.610 --> 00:13:30.680
really meaningful and deep.

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:32.440
SPEAKER 1: I guess
I didn't realize

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:34.120
that the bad guy
with the green screen

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:36.250
was never preconceived
beforehand.

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:37.833
REESE WITHERSPOON:
Sometimes they are,

00:13:37.833 --> 00:13:40.330
and sometimes they have no
idea what's coming next.

00:13:43.250 --> 00:13:47.862
SPEAKER 1: So working
with the Three Stooges--

00:13:47.862 --> 00:13:49.570
was there any parallel
there, by the way?

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:51.320
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: No.

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:52.450
SPEAKER 1: Why three guys?

00:13:52.450 --> 00:13:53.380
I'm sidetracking here.

00:13:53.380 --> 00:13:54.100
Why three guys?

00:13:54.100 --> 00:13:54.630
Why not one?

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:55.997
Why not two?

00:13:55.997 --> 00:13:58.330
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: I think
good things come in threes.

00:13:58.330 --> 00:14:01.354
It just was always going to be
a trio for me, I don't know.

00:14:01.354 --> 00:14:02.020
SPEAKER 1: Fair.

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:03.470
OK, so back to my
original thought.

00:14:03.470 --> 00:14:04.420
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
It was always three.

00:14:04.420 --> 00:14:05.410
SPEAKER 1: So this
is a little bit of a.

00:14:05.410 --> 00:14:07.299
Spoiler some of you
have seen the movie.

00:14:07.299 --> 00:14:08.590
We screened it here last night.

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:11.219
So at the end, I was
pleasantly surprised

00:14:11.219 --> 00:14:12.760
to find that at the
end of the story,

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:16.850
Alice doesn't choose
any of the men.

00:14:16.850 --> 00:14:19.217
Which is great.

00:14:19.217 --> 00:14:20.800
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
They just gasped.

00:14:20.800 --> 00:14:22.898
REESE WITHERSPOON: Oh no.

00:14:22.898 --> 00:14:24.470
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
Imagine that.

00:14:24.470 --> 00:14:27.870
SPEAKER 1: You don't
need a man to be happy?

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:29.710
And it's refreshing to
see a romantic comedy

00:14:29.710 --> 00:14:35.730
where the female protagonist
finds happiness on her own.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:36.564
Jon, I'd choose you.

00:14:36.564 --> 00:14:38.813
REESE WITHERSPOON: Do you
know how many people come up

00:14:38.813 --> 00:14:40.120
to me like, what about Jon?

00:14:40.120 --> 00:14:41.595
What about the
guy, that Jon guy?

00:14:41.595 --> 00:14:43.970
SPEAKER 1: I did think that
you were going to go for Jon.

00:14:43.970 --> 00:14:45.010
That Alice would go for Jon.

00:14:45.010 --> 00:14:45.940
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: So many
people say that to me, too.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:47.170
JON RUDNITSKY: Yeah,
I'm writing a sequel

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:48.211
where we end up together.

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:53.150
"Home Again, Again."

00:14:53.150 --> 00:14:54.940
SPEAKER 1: "Still Home Again."

00:14:58.090 --> 00:15:00.700
I guess is one of the
most powerful things

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:03.370
about this movie, is that I
feel every woman is portrayed

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:08.360
as a strong woman, even like the
smaller supporting characters.

00:15:08.360 --> 00:15:11.170
None of them are typically
your frail, weak sort

00:15:11.170 --> 00:15:14.632
of women that are
often portrayed.

00:15:14.632 --> 00:15:16.840
Was this a conscious choice
when you were writing it?

00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:18.850
And I guess for you,
Reese, was this something

00:15:18.850 --> 00:15:23.620
you noticed in the script that
attracted you to the role?

00:15:23.620 --> 00:15:29.080
REESE WITHERSPOON: Yeah, I
don't play a lot of weak women.

00:15:29.080 --> 00:15:31.240
I don't really know
any weak women.

00:15:34.877 --> 00:15:37.210
My mother used to always say,
if you want to be a woman,

00:15:37.210 --> 00:15:38.415
you'd better be tough.

00:15:38.415 --> 00:15:40.630
And that's the only
kind of women I know.

00:15:40.630 --> 00:15:42.377
That's what Hallie writes.

00:15:42.377 --> 00:15:43.960
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
I wouldn't have--

00:15:43.960 --> 00:15:45.130
I don't know.

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:47.460
I also don't know
any weak women.

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:49.630
It wouldn't have come
naturally to me to write that.

00:15:49.630 --> 00:15:51.770
She's vulnerable,
that's for sure.

00:15:51.770 --> 00:15:53.500
And she gains
strength by the end

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:56.470
of the film, and
self-confidence, and feeling

00:15:56.470 --> 00:16:00.130
like she's going to
be OK by the end.

00:16:00.130 --> 00:16:02.510
I wasn't consciously thinking,
this is a strong woman.

00:16:02.510 --> 00:16:05.710
I just thought, this as a
woman, and women are strong.

00:16:05.710 --> 00:16:07.890
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, I agree.

00:16:07.890 --> 00:16:08.640
Very well written.

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:09.910
And so Erika--

00:16:09.910 --> 00:16:10.600
Olde?

00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:12.356
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: Yeah, Olde.

00:16:12.356 --> 00:16:13.730
SPEAKER 1: Produced
this as well.

00:16:13.730 --> 00:16:17.030
So she's only been producing
for just a few years, too.

00:16:17.030 --> 00:16:18.946
She's a new producer.

00:16:18.946 --> 00:16:20.320
And I was reading
up on her, too,

00:16:20.320 --> 00:16:25.670
and she produces films
primarily made by women as well.

00:16:25.670 --> 00:16:27.010
So how did you find her?

00:16:27.010 --> 00:16:28.654
How did she become attached?

00:16:28.654 --> 00:16:30.820
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: After
I had written the script,

00:16:30.820 --> 00:16:32.770
we gave it to our
agents, who wanted

00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:34.660
to help us get the
financing for this movie.

00:16:34.660 --> 00:16:36.670
And Erika was the
right person, I think,

00:16:36.670 --> 00:16:40.810
because her whole company is
based around women's stories.

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:43.780
And I think she
has a particular--

00:16:43.780 --> 00:16:46.720
she loves these kinds
of movies, and she

00:16:46.720 --> 00:16:49.690
wanted to tell women's stories
and help female directors.

00:16:49.690 --> 00:16:51.370
So it was a really nice pairing.

00:16:51.370 --> 00:16:55.540
And she's a young woman
herself, and it was great.

00:16:55.540 --> 00:16:56.740
SPEAKER 1: That's wonderful.

00:16:56.740 --> 00:16:58.690
So Reese, a little
side question, I guess.

00:16:58.690 --> 00:17:00.880
Over the last few
years, so you've

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:02.470
been getting into
producing yourself.

00:17:02.470 --> 00:17:03.970
And you produced
"Big Little Lies,"

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:09.849
which now you have a bajillion
Emmy nominations for that,

00:17:09.849 --> 00:17:12.040
which is wonderful.

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:15.380
What made you want to
get into producing?

00:17:15.380 --> 00:17:17.619
REESE WITHERSPOON: Well,
about five years ago, I

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:19.420
read probably the
worst script I've ever

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:20.960
read in my entire life.

00:17:20.960 --> 00:17:26.859
And the part for a woman was
just absolutely dreadful.

00:17:26.859 --> 00:17:27.634
Opposite a guy.

00:17:27.634 --> 00:17:29.050
And I called my
agent, and I said,

00:17:29.050 --> 00:17:30.410
well, this is just
a piece of crap,

00:17:30.410 --> 00:17:31.576
and I don't want to do this.

00:17:31.576 --> 00:17:35.410
And she said, every actress
in Hollywood wants this part.

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:39.280
And I thought, we deserve
better than these parts.

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:41.489
And so I was like,
I can either start

00:17:41.489 --> 00:17:43.780
complaining about it, which
isn't going to do any good,

00:17:43.780 --> 00:17:45.290
or I can do something about it.

00:17:45.290 --> 00:17:48.460
So I started buying books
and turning them into movies.

00:17:48.460 --> 00:17:51.610
And my first two were
"Wild" and "Gone Girl."

00:17:51.610 --> 00:17:54.400
And so I just started
from there, and creating

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:56.180
parts for other women as well.

00:17:56.180 --> 00:17:59.030
And that's sort of been the
next chapter of my life.

00:17:59.030 --> 00:18:01.720
SPEAKER 1: So do you enjoy
performing still more?

00:18:01.720 --> 00:18:03.825
Or are you aiming more
towards the producer side

00:18:03.825 --> 00:18:04.450
moving forward?

00:18:04.450 --> 00:18:05.660
REESE WITHERSPOON: No,
I like being an actor.

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:06.460
I really love it.

00:18:06.460 --> 00:18:07.390
It's my first love.

00:18:07.390 --> 00:18:09.070
I get on set, and
I get all excited.

00:18:09.070 --> 00:18:10.920
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
She's so good at it.

00:18:10.920 --> 00:18:13.690
REESE WITHERSPOON: I enjoy
it, but I love producing.

00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:18.960
And I'm really a big
reader, so I read a ton.

00:18:18.960 --> 00:18:20.887
And I kind of have
an eye for what

00:18:20.887 --> 00:18:22.970
is actually going to remain,
and what's cinematic.

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:25.534
Because not every book is--

00:18:25.534 --> 00:18:26.950
things can be
beautifully written,

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:28.530
but just it's not
going to happen.

00:18:28.530 --> 00:18:30.790
And I think those
two things together

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:33.824
really help create a
successful producing career.

00:18:33.824 --> 00:18:35.365
SPEAKER 1: You should
produce a movie

00:18:35.365 --> 00:18:36.910
you star in where
you play a doctor,

00:18:36.910 --> 00:18:38.520
and it would satisfy everything.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:40.270
REESE WITHERSPOON: I
should, you're right.

00:18:40.270 --> 00:18:41.520
SPEAKER 1: Be a brain surgeon.

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:43.690
"Thanks, Mom."

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:45.580
Going back, I guess,
to the casting,

00:18:45.580 --> 00:18:48.940
you have two wonderful
children that you cast.

00:18:48.940 --> 00:18:53.260
Lola Flanery and
Eden Grace Redfield.

00:18:53.260 --> 00:18:56.950
Is it harder to cast
roles for children

00:18:56.950 --> 00:18:58.210
or to cast roles for adults?

00:18:58.210 --> 00:19:00.730
And specifically for these
two kids, how did you find it?

00:19:00.730 --> 00:19:02.980
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER: It's
really hard to cast children

00:19:02.980 --> 00:19:06.610
because their parents
rehearse it with them.

00:19:06.610 --> 00:19:09.807
So it's hard sometimes-- when
I was watching the auditions,

00:19:09.807 --> 00:19:12.390
it would be like they've had a
very specific way of saying it,

00:19:12.390 --> 00:19:13.330
and a specific rhythm.

00:19:13.330 --> 00:19:15.750
And you feel like you might
have to undo that a lot.

00:19:15.750 --> 00:19:17.920
But these two kids,
you could just

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:20.110
feel that there was
something supernatural--

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:25.260
not supernatural, but
very natural about them.

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:26.760
SPEAKER 1: They
were sort of ghosty.

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:28.468
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
Well, the little one

00:19:28.468 --> 00:19:31.570
caught my eye, honestly,
because she was Reese's twin.

00:19:31.570 --> 00:19:33.820
And we were like, that's
just a little Reese.

00:19:33.820 --> 00:19:36.910
And then she happened to have
this fantastic comedic timing

00:19:36.910 --> 00:19:38.840
and be super unique.

00:19:38.840 --> 00:19:42.370
And Lola, I really
wanted somebody

00:19:42.370 --> 00:19:46.305
in that part that could play
the comedy of being anxious,

00:19:46.305 --> 00:19:48.430
but you wouldn't actually
be super worried for her.

00:19:48.430 --> 00:19:50.170
You just felt like
this was a stage

00:19:50.170 --> 00:19:51.378
she was going to come out of.

00:19:51.378 --> 00:19:54.600
And I think Lola has kind of
an inner happiness to her.

00:19:54.600 --> 00:19:57.980
She's very sweet, and then
the sweetness comes through.

00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:00.880
And I think they just
both were so natural.

00:20:00.880 --> 00:20:06.120
They didn't feel child actory.

