doing stand-up.

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:24.654
REESE WITHERSPOON: Yeah.

00:29:24.654 --> 00:29:25.570
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
That's so great.

00:29:25.570 --> 00:29:26.778
REESE WITHERSPOON: Go, Karen.

00:29:26.778 --> 00:29:28.550
JON RUDNITSKY: Yeah,
that's pretty cool.

00:29:28.550 --> 00:29:31.760
She's going to freak when she
finds out that you asked this.

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:34.480
And yeah, my mom tells
a story about when

00:29:34.480 --> 00:29:37.360
I went to sleepaway camp.

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:41.110
My parents are divorced,
and my dad's very Type A,

00:29:41.110 --> 00:29:42.580
and my mom's a total mess.

00:29:42.580 --> 00:29:44.750
And my dad called her.

00:29:44.750 --> 00:29:48.100
He was like, you put Jon's
name on all the clothes, right?

00:29:48.100 --> 00:29:50.564
You labeled his name
on all the clothes?

00:29:50.564 --> 00:29:52.480
My mom was like, oh yes,
of course, of course.

00:29:52.480 --> 00:29:56.890
And she immediately hired
somebody to put the labels on.

00:29:56.890 --> 00:29:59.710
But when they were all
done, it said my name

00:29:59.710 --> 00:30:02.830
on the front of everything.

00:30:02.830 --> 00:30:07.910
So it was like, down my zipper
and across my hat and stuff.

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:11.370
My mom's whole joke is when
I got back, I was crying.

00:30:11.370 --> 00:30:13.670
And I said, I didn't
make any friends,

00:30:13.670 --> 00:30:17.460
but everybody knew my name.

00:30:17.460 --> 00:30:18.835
AUDIENCE: It got
a lot of laughs.

00:30:18.835 --> 00:30:20.334
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
That's amazing.

00:30:20.334 --> 00:30:22.026
AUDIENCE: But my
question is for Reese.

00:30:29.490 --> 00:30:31.144
REESE WITHERSPOON:
That was so funny.

00:30:31.144 --> 00:30:33.060
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
That was just her opener.

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:34.030
REESE WITHERSPOON: Yeah,
that was really funny.

00:30:34.030 --> 00:30:35.196
JON RUDNITSKY: That's great.

00:30:35.196 --> 00:30:39.530
You should do an open mic at
the Comic Strip with my mom.

00:30:39.530 --> 00:30:41.280
AUDIENCE: So I'm also
a really big reader.

00:30:41.280 --> 00:30:43.872
In fact, on Pacific
Standard's last movies

00:30:43.872 --> 00:30:46.080
have been my favorite books
from the last five years.

00:30:46.080 --> 00:30:48.800
So it's been really exciting.

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:51.250
But my question is,
so how do know--

00:30:51.250 --> 00:30:54.159
I'm a very big believer
that the books are always

00:30:54.159 --> 00:30:54.950
better than movies.

00:30:54.950 --> 00:30:57.465
But it's been really
enjoyable to watch

00:30:57.465 --> 00:30:59.840
all of my favorite books in
the last couple of years been

00:30:59.840 --> 00:31:01.730
these amazing movies and shows.

00:31:01.730 --> 00:31:04.760
So how do you know when
you're reading something

00:31:04.760 --> 00:31:08.310
that this is going to translate
really well to the screen?

00:31:08.310 --> 00:31:10.360
REESE WITHERSPOON: That's
a really good question.

00:31:10.360 --> 00:31:11.900
It's a little complicated.

00:31:11.900 --> 00:31:14.670
I think because knowing
what people will actually

00:31:14.670 --> 00:31:16.250
buy and turn into a movie.

00:31:16.250 --> 00:31:19.560
If it's two sisters during
the French Revolution,

00:31:19.560 --> 00:31:21.300
it's just not going
to be a movie.

00:31:21.300 --> 00:31:25.110
It's too expensive,
it's too niche.

00:31:25.110 --> 00:31:27.240
So I think I try to
find things that are

00:31:27.240 --> 00:31:29.920
universal, kind of relatable.

00:31:29.920 --> 00:31:33.540
And my main directive has
just been have a woman

00:31:33.540 --> 00:31:35.550
at the center of it
doing something--

00:31:35.550 --> 00:31:39.870
sort of telling another aspect
of the female experience.

00:31:39.870 --> 00:31:43.890
So "Gone Girl" is like, I
don't know, is she psychotic?

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:44.740
I don't know.

00:31:44.740 --> 00:31:48.120
But it's something that took
an idea of the perfect girl

00:31:48.120 --> 00:31:49.680
and kind of flipped
it on its head.

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:52.320
And "Wild," I loved the idea
of a woman versus nature.

00:31:52.320 --> 00:31:54.870
Because you see men versus
nature all the time, right?

00:31:54.870 --> 00:31:57.030
And then I never really
thought about what's

00:31:57.030 --> 00:32:00.300
the movie where women are
up against the environment

00:32:00.300 --> 00:32:02.010
by themselves.

00:32:02.010 --> 00:32:05.130
So it's just stuff like that,
things that feel fresh and new.

00:32:05.130 --> 00:32:06.200
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:32:06.200 --> 00:32:06.870
SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:32:06.870 --> 00:32:08.040
Over here?

00:32:08.040 --> 00:32:09.630
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:32:09.630 --> 00:32:13.500
So Reese, you talked about
the availability of roles

00:32:13.500 --> 00:32:15.420
for men and women.

00:32:15.420 --> 00:32:18.439
Over your 20 years
in the industry,

00:32:18.439 --> 00:32:19.980
have you seen that
evolve, and do you

00:32:19.980 --> 00:32:21.396
feel like we're
at a point in time

00:32:21.396 --> 00:32:23.640
where there's a lot of
momentum for roles for women?

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:24.744
Or how does that work?

00:32:24.744 --> 00:32:26.160
REESE WITHERSPOON:
Yeah, I mean, I

00:32:26.160 --> 00:32:28.680
think it's a better
time than ever.

00:32:28.680 --> 00:32:30.670
But I have to say,
when I started,

00:32:30.670 --> 00:32:33.414
it was a good time
for women's movies.

00:32:33.414 --> 00:32:35.080
Women were the stars
of their own movies

00:32:35.080 --> 00:32:36.810
at the time I came up.

00:32:36.810 --> 00:32:38.340
I was lucky I got
in a window where

00:32:38.340 --> 00:32:40.381
I made "Legally Blonde"
and "Sweet Home Alabama,"

00:32:40.381 --> 00:32:42.840
and I could be the
lead of a movie.

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:46.230
I think it's harder now,
particularly in movies.

00:32:46.230 --> 00:32:50.250
You don't see women being the
star of movies very often.

00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:52.530
I've heard people still
say straight to my face.

00:32:52.530 --> 00:32:55.410
"We have one movie that has a
woman starring in it this year,

00:32:55.410 --> 00:32:58.390
we don't need another one."

00:32:58.390 --> 00:33:01.140
But the great news is with
all these streaming services

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:07.050
and the new platforms, now they
need content more than ever.

00:33:07.050 --> 00:33:10.020
And that creates opportunity
for women of all ages, women

00:33:10.020 --> 00:33:12.580
of all color.

00:33:12.580 --> 00:33:14.700
So it's really kind of
broadening the spectrum

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:16.595
and creating more roles.

00:33:16.595 --> 00:33:17.481
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:33:17.481 --> 00:33:18.814
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, back over here.

00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:24.190
AUDIENCE: I wanted to thank
you guys for being here.

00:33:24.190 --> 00:33:26.710
Hallie, you mentioned earlier
that you felt like you

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:28.320
were making a feel-good movie.

00:33:28.320 --> 00:33:31.230
And I feel like we all
need that right now.

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:33.960
So thank you.

00:33:33.960 --> 00:33:38.640
And then Reese, I just wanted
to say I was thinking yesterday

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:40.822
while I was watching
the movie, you're

00:33:40.822 --> 00:33:42.030
one of my favorite actresses.

00:33:42.030 --> 00:33:43.821
What would I say if
you were actually here,

00:33:43.821 --> 00:33:46.770
and actually at Google.

00:33:46.770 --> 00:33:49.080
And I was thinking
about how you've

00:33:49.080 --> 00:33:52.050
had this history of
performing in "Election,"

00:33:52.050 --> 00:33:53.280
in "Cruel Intentions."

00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:56.400
All these women who are not
just strong but sort of strong

00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:58.299
in ways that people
don't want them to be,

00:33:58.299 --> 00:34:00.090
or don't quite understand,
and that they're

00:34:00.090 --> 00:34:04.540
successful in ways that
don't fit with expectations.

00:34:04.540 --> 00:34:07.170
And I think that's sort of
a really interesting message

00:34:07.170 --> 00:34:10.980
for the women in Google
right now, many of whom

00:34:10.980 --> 00:34:14.870
are in roles that people
don't expect them to be in,

00:34:14.870 --> 00:34:18.050
or don't quite trust
them to be successful in.

00:34:18.050 --> 00:34:21.224
And it's your particular
history of performance

00:34:21.224 --> 00:34:23.570
is an interesting one right now.

00:34:23.570 --> 00:34:26.600
And I'm not shocked to see this
many women here in this room

00:34:26.600 --> 00:34:29.540
and screaming for "Legally
Blonde" and Tracy Flick,

00:34:29.540 --> 00:34:32.550
although she was left
out of your recitation.

00:34:32.550 --> 00:34:34.370
So I just wanted to
thank you for that.

00:34:34.370 --> 00:34:37.675
And also, hi, Jon.

00:34:37.675 --> 00:34:41.056
Your mom sounds cool.

00:34:41.056 --> 00:34:42.505
REESE WITHERSPOON: Thank you.

00:34:42.505 --> 00:34:43.471
Thank you, [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:43.471 --> 00:34:45.420
Thank you.

00:34:45.420 --> 00:34:47.864
JON RUDNITSKY: Sweet.

00:34:47.864 --> 00:34:48.907
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:34:48.907 --> 00:34:50.406
I feel like I have
so many questions

00:34:50.406 --> 00:34:52.489
to ask Reese, because I
feel like we would be best

00:34:52.489 --> 00:34:54.250
friends if we ever [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:54.250 --> 00:34:56.219
REESE WITHERSPOON: I
think we probably would.

00:34:56.219 --> 00:34:57.927
AUDIENCE: But you
actually said something

00:34:57.927 --> 00:34:59.950
that changed my whole
question dynamic before.

00:34:59.950 --> 00:35:02.170
You said there was a script
that you read that was

00:35:02.170 --> 00:35:03.820
really crappy for the woman.

00:35:03.820 --> 00:35:05.530
Did that ever get made?

00:35:05.530 --> 00:35:07.830
REESE WITHERSPOON:
Yep, sure did.

00:35:07.830 --> 00:35:10.072
Win an Oscar-winning
actress for the part.

00:35:10.072 --> 00:35:10.780
AUDIENCE: Really?

00:35:10.780 --> 00:35:12.180
Are you able to say what movie?

00:35:12.180 --> 00:35:13.350
REESE WITHERSPOON: No, I'm not.

00:35:13.350 --> 00:35:14.426
JON RUDNITSKY: Did it do well?

00:35:14.426 --> 00:35:16.030
Or that got nominated
for Academy Award?

00:35:16.030 --> 00:35:17.446
REESE WITHERSPOON:
No, it did not.

00:35:17.446 --> 00:35:19.030
I was a terrible movie.

00:35:19.030 --> 00:35:22.090
But you know, I've always
had a thing where--

00:35:22.090 --> 00:35:24.519
back to your point
about being a woman who

00:35:24.519 --> 00:35:25.810
does sort of unorthodox things.

00:35:25.810 --> 00:35:27.640
I turned down so
many parts where--

00:35:27.640 --> 00:35:30.139
I got a lot of opportunity
after "Legally Blonde"

00:35:30.139 --> 00:35:31.930
to play the girlfriend
in superhero movies.

00:35:31.930 --> 00:35:33.599
Girlfriend,
girlfriend-- I was like,

00:35:33.599 --> 00:35:35.890
why would I be the girlfriend
when I could be the lead?

00:35:35.890 --> 00:35:38.306
I would rather take less money
and be the lead of a movie,

00:35:38.306 --> 00:35:40.720
show a girl that she can be
the center of her own story,

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:44.140
than be a very
wealthy girlfriend.

00:35:44.140 --> 00:35:47.520
Because it doesn't
move the needle for me.

00:35:47.520 --> 00:35:50.200
And I also had a little
girl when I was 23.

00:35:50.200 --> 00:35:52.570
So it kind of shifted
my perspective

00:35:52.570 --> 00:35:55.750
of what do I want
her to see on film.

00:35:55.750 --> 00:35:59.170
I grew up with Holly Hunter, and
Debra Winger, and Diane Keaton,

00:35:59.170 --> 00:36:00.260
and Meg Ryan.

00:36:00.260 --> 00:36:02.890
And those were events for me
when they had movies coming out

00:36:02.890 --> 00:36:03.730
on a Friday night.

00:36:03.730 --> 00:36:07.540
That's what I wanted to see,
a woman who's figuring it out.

00:36:07.540 --> 00:36:09.550
She doesn't know what
the next step of her life

00:36:09.550 --> 00:36:10.390
is going to be.

00:36:10.390 --> 00:36:12.761
And I just think that's
what drives me every day.

00:36:12.761 --> 00:36:15.010
That's why I have a mission
just to create those parts

00:36:15.010 --> 00:36:17.890
for myself, for other
women, for female directors

00:36:17.890 --> 00:36:20.680
to have the opportunity to
tell women's perspectives.

00:36:20.680 --> 00:36:24.220
Because if we don't see
women's perspectives--

00:36:24.220 --> 00:36:26.170
I mean, we've talked about this.

00:36:26.170 --> 00:36:28.750
Women in women's films
treat men differently.

00:36:28.750 --> 00:36:30.370
The men treat the
women differently.

00:36:30.370 --> 00:36:32.350
That's a narrative
that's important.

00:36:32.350 --> 00:36:34.670
And I would say the same
thing about women of color,

00:36:34.670 --> 00:36:37.720
women of different generations.

00:36:37.720 --> 00:36:39.880
All different perspectives
need to be represented.

00:36:39.880 --> 00:36:41.020
And it's just enough.

00:36:41.020 --> 00:36:44.260
I've had enough of the same
people telling the same dang

00:36:44.260 --> 00:36:45.580
stories.

00:36:45.580 --> 00:36:47.800
If we don't see some
new perspectives,

00:36:47.800 --> 00:36:49.630
society can't
change, and we can't

00:36:49.630 --> 00:36:51.190
have different conversations.

00:36:51.190 --> 00:36:55.166
And that's how I feel about it.

00:36:55.166 --> 00:36:55.958
JON RUDNITSKY: Wow.

00:36:55.958 --> 00:36:58.207
REESE WITHERSPOON: But I
don't really have an opinion.

00:36:58.207 --> 00:36:59.940
JON RUDNITSKY: No,
no, no, not at all.

00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:01.486
SPEAKER 1: And thank you to Jon.

00:37:01.486 --> 00:37:02.694
JON RUDNITSKY: Also, hi, Jon.

00:37:02.694 --> 00:37:03.998
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:37:03.998 --> 00:37:05.392
And my mom, whatever.

00:37:05.392 --> 00:37:06.600
REESE WITHERSPOON: And Karen.

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:07.870
JON RUDNITSKY: And
Karen, of course.

00:37:07.870 --> 00:37:08.930
SPEAKER 1: Back over here.

00:37:08.930 --> 00:37:09.721
AUDIENCE: Hi, guys.

00:37:09.721 --> 00:37:11.580
My name is Brooke
Taylor, which is actually

00:37:11.580 --> 00:37:13.365
a character in "Legally Blonde."

00:37:13.365 --> 00:37:17.689
Which made me super popular
in fifth grade, so thank you.

00:37:17.689 --> 00:37:19.980
And a question I got to asked
on my first day at Google

00:37:19.980 --> 00:37:23.400
is if I could have lunch
with anyone dead or alive,

00:37:23.400 --> 00:37:24.190
who would it be?

00:37:24.190 --> 00:37:25.200
And I said Elle Woods.

00:37:25.200 --> 00:37:28.710
And that made me even more
popular, so thank you.

00:37:28.710 --> 00:37:30.810
Thank you very much for
the "Glamour" article.

00:37:30.810 --> 00:37:33.275
I'm sure that's been
circulating quite a bit.

00:37:33.275 --> 00:37:34.650
You have a lot of
ambitious women

00:37:34.650 --> 00:37:37.200
in the room who are strong not
because they're strong women,

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:39.590
but because we're women,
and that's what women are.

00:37:39.590 --> 00:37:41.340
Can you speak a little
bit to the article,

00:37:41.340 --> 00:37:43.927
and just give us some
advice, and even talk

00:37:43.927 --> 00:37:45.510
about how it's been
received if you've

00:37:45.510 --> 00:37:46.862
gotten any sort of feedback?

00:37:46.862 --> 00:37:49.320
REESE WITHERSPOON: Well, thank
you so much for saying that.

00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:51.000
I worked really hard
on that article.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:54.300
I probably did 30
drafts, because I

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:57.250
think it's really
important what you say.

00:37:57.250 --> 00:37:58.650
Probably like,
three years ago, I

00:37:58.650 --> 00:38:00.733
was asked to give a speech
at this "Glamour" event

00:38:00.733 --> 00:38:04.290
about ambition and women,
and why that's considered

00:38:04.290 --> 00:38:06.480
a negative trait in women.

00:38:06.480 --> 00:38:08.280
And they did this
study at Columbia

00:38:08.280 --> 00:38:11.050
that identified it as a
negative trait in a coworker,

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:13.200
as a female coworker,
that she's seen

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:15.030
as selfish or self-serving.

00:38:15.030 --> 00:38:18.360
And I thought, why has
become such a negative thing?

00:38:18.360 --> 00:38:20.320
I was always ambitious,
even as a little girl.

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:22.140
I didn't know you were
supposed to hide it.

00:38:22.140 --> 00:38:24.300
So there's a new
Harvard study that women

00:38:24.300 --> 00:38:29.760
who are seen as a vicious
hide it if they're single.

00:38:29.760 --> 00:38:32.550
That just drove me up a
wall, because I thought,

00:38:32.550 --> 00:38:34.320
run away from anybody
who doesn't like

00:38:34.320 --> 00:38:36.780
your ambition, particularly
a guy or a partner.

00:38:36.780 --> 00:38:38.560
Because it should be encouraged.

00:38:38.560 --> 00:38:40.290
And it's not the
self-serving thing.

00:38:40.290 --> 00:38:44.100
It's like most women who are
ambitious have a bigger goal.

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:47.910
We're community leaders,
we're strong family leaders,

00:38:47.910 --> 00:38:50.910
we can change a lot and
create a lot of change.

00:38:50.910 --> 00:38:54.990
But we're stymied
because of this stigma

00:38:54.990 --> 00:38:55.949
around being ambitious.

00:38:55.949 --> 00:38:57.489
I think it's why a
lot of women don't

00:38:57.489 --> 00:38:59.260
run for office, because
we look at women

00:38:59.260 --> 00:39:01.464
and go, of course
she wants to win.

00:39:01.464 --> 00:39:02.380
Why shouldn't she win?

00:39:02.380 --> 00:39:05.065
She's probably going to help us.

00:39:05.065 --> 00:39:06.440
And I think we
have to change it.

00:39:06.440 --> 00:39:07.856
We have to start
talking about it.

