mostly for Reese,

00:49:28.360 --> 00:49:30.318
but I would love to hear
Hallie's thoughts too,

00:49:30.318 --> 00:49:31.390
if you have any.

00:49:31.390 --> 00:49:33.100
Obviously I love
"Legally Blonde,"

00:49:33.100 --> 00:49:38.010
but one of my favorite movies
of yours actually is "Freeway."

00:49:38.010 --> 00:49:42.220
I was thinking about
the how a lot of people

00:49:42.220 --> 00:49:45.580
see women in action movies,
and how just a woman punching

00:49:45.580 --> 00:49:48.250
someone or shooting someone
can be just enough for people

00:49:48.250 --> 00:49:50.410
to give them the strong
female character label.

00:49:50.410 --> 00:49:52.150
But obviously
there's like-- you've

00:49:52.150 --> 00:49:54.580
been doing so many
romcoms, and comedies,

00:49:54.580 --> 00:49:55.504
and "Big Little Lies."

00:49:55.504 --> 00:49:56.920
And I was wondering
what you think

00:49:56.920 --> 00:50:02.710
of the difference in value of
a strong woman in a comedy,

00:50:02.710 --> 00:50:06.550
versus like a family drama,
versus an action movie,

00:50:06.550 --> 00:50:08.350
like "Freeway," or
some more recent ones,

00:50:08.350 --> 00:50:12.790
like "Mad Max" and
"Atomic Blonde."

00:50:12.790 --> 00:50:15.470
REESE WITHERSPOON: All of
those genres are great.

00:50:15.470 --> 00:50:17.770
And I think more
that like looking

00:50:17.770 --> 00:50:20.980
for strong or weak, and
look, I answer that question,

00:50:20.980 --> 00:50:23.035
because I think of myself
as a strong person.

00:50:23.035 --> 00:50:26.260
But I'm just looking for
complexity, because women just

00:50:26.260 --> 00:50:28.190
aren't good or bad.

00:50:28.190 --> 00:50:30.610
There's this whole rainbow
of other things in between,

00:50:30.610 --> 00:50:31.435
you know?

00:50:31.435 --> 00:50:36.370
They're complex, and confused,
and contemplating things.

00:50:36.370 --> 00:50:41.140
And some of them are just
plain strange, I don't know.

00:50:41.140 --> 00:50:43.060
I want to see every
color of the rainbow.

00:50:43.060 --> 00:50:44.800
I don't want to just see--

00:50:44.800 --> 00:50:47.757
I don't know, sometimes I think
you just get watered down.

00:50:47.757 --> 00:50:49.840
It gets watered down because
they don't understand

00:50:49.840 --> 00:50:51.298
the complexity of
the female brain,

00:50:51.298 --> 00:50:54.734
because you're not
a woman writing it.

00:50:54.734 --> 00:50:55.600
Yeah.

00:50:55.600 --> 00:50:56.500
What do you think?

00:50:56.500 --> 00:50:56.950
HALLIE MEYERS-SHYER:
I don't know.

00:50:56.950 --> 00:50:59.230
I mean, I don't see a
ton of action movies.

00:50:59.230 --> 00:51:03.670
It's just not, as an audience
member, my favorite genre.

00:51:03.670 --> 00:51:06.250
But I do think sometimes
the women in those movies

00:51:06.250 --> 00:51:09.220
are considered strong because
they're acting like men.

00:51:09.220 --> 00:51:11.760
And for me, the characters
that have meant most to me,

00:51:11.760 --> 00:51:13.176
the ones that Reese
has portrayed,

00:51:13.176 --> 00:51:16.060
are strong because they're
complex, and they're real.

00:51:16.060 --> 00:51:17.980
There's something
real about them.

00:51:17.980 --> 00:51:20.438
I don't think you see a woman
in an action movie and think,

00:51:20.438 --> 00:51:21.520
that's me.

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:24.237
I'm just like her
in "Atomic Blonde."

00:51:24.237 --> 00:51:26.320
Even though it can be super
entertaining and great

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:28.600
to watch, for me,
it's the relatability

00:51:28.600 --> 00:51:30.880
of a character that--

00:51:30.880 --> 00:51:33.190
if you see Reese on
screen being strong,

00:51:33.190 --> 00:51:35.170
and she's going
through separation,

00:51:35.170 --> 00:51:36.580
that might give you--

00:51:36.580 --> 00:51:37.690
I can do it, too.

00:51:37.690 --> 00:51:40.150
And I think that's, for me,
where the strength comes

00:51:40.150 --> 00:51:42.890
from on screen.

